SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 542
By Johnson
A RESOLUTION to honor and celebrate the seventy-fifth
anniversary of the Franklin Rodeo.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we honor and congratulate those community events that
have been sources of great civic pride and are celebrating historic milestones; and
WHEREAS, one such event is the Franklin Rodeo, for which cowboys and cowgirls,
since 1949, have stampeded to Franklin each May to take part in what is proudly billed as one
of the largest rodeos east of the Mississippi River; and
WHEREAS, for seventy-five years, the Franklin Rodeo has been presented by the
Franklin Noon Rotary Club, which was chartered on January 13, 1948, with just fourteen
members; today, the organization has over 160 active and honorary members, representing a
diverse cross-section of business and community leaders; and
WHEREAS, searching for a fundraising project that would make a meaningful impact,
the members of the Franklin Noon Rotary Club settled on a rodeo, which had been championed
by Dr. Harry Guffee, John Fowlkes, Preston Fowlkes, and Bob Corley, with key contributions by
Ed Moody, who managed the rodeo from the 1950s until 1984; and
WHEREAS, the first Franklin Rodeo was held on Saturday, May 6, 1949, complete with
a parade that captured the spirit of the community, led by Governor Gordon Browning and
joined by local Rotarians, visiting cowboys, Franklin High School and Columbia Military
Academy bands, and approximately 1,000 4-H members and their families; and
WHEREAS, although the rodeo's early years were challenging, today, the Franklin
Rodeo stands as a testament to the resilience and character of the Franklin Noon Rotary Club
and the community it serves; and
SJR0542
009662
- 1 -

WHEREAS, over the past seven decades, the Franklin Rodeo has generated millions of
dollars to support a variety of community causes, including financial aid for scholarships to
medical, dental, and nursing schools and public school needs such as band uniforms and library
books; and
WHEREAS, with an annual attendance of over 19,000, the Franklin Rodeo has been
officially sanctioned by the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association since 2005; the event now
spans three nights, takes place in an air-conditioned arena, and features nationally ranked
contestants and top-tier bucking stock; and
WHEREAS, it is highly appropriate that we recognize the Franklin Rodeo and
congratulate the event's organizers on this special occasion; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the Franklin Rodeo on the occasion of its
seventy-fifth anniversary, extending our appreciation to all those involved with this event and
offering our best wishes for much continued success in the years to come.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
